{
  "style": "IEEE",
  "texts": [
    "Such states are arguably natural from two perspectives.",
    "The first is one from the quantum Hall effect: various perturbations away from the idealized holomorphic structure of the lowest Landau level can favour spatially inhomogeneous ground states, albeit for partial filling of a single Landau level.",
    "These can often be captured in a Hartree-Fock treatment [287,288], which for certain choices of interaction becomes exact in the limit of large Landau level index n [289], in consonance with the experimental observation of stripe and bubble phases in higher Landau levels [290].",
    "Given that the chiral-flat limit has a close connection to the lowest Landau level, we might expect that a similar situation might arise on moving away from this limit (although in this case we are working at integer filling, so the analogy is not immediate).",
    "The second comes from considering extended Hubbard models: owing to the topological obstructions of the flat bands, any Hubbard-type description naturally has extended interactions, which are known to stabilize stripeordered states [291][292][293][294][295][296][297][298][299][300][301][302]."
  ],
  "correct_citations": [
